.Dd March 30, 2026
.Dt VIS 1
.Os Kayoko
.Sh NAME
.Nm vis ,
.Nm unvis
.Nd display non-printable characters or decode them
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm vis
.Op Ar file ...
.Nm unvis
.Op Ar file ...
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm vis
utility reads the given files (or standard input if no files are specified)
and writes the content to standard output, converting non-printable
characters into a visible representation.
.Pp
The
.Nm unvis
utility performs the inverse operation, decoding visual representations
(like
.Li \en
or
.Li \e001 )
back into their original raw byte form.
.Pp
Characters are processed as follows in
.Nm vis :
.Bl -bullet -offset indent
.It
Printable ASCII characters are passed through unchanged.
.It
Common control characters are represented by standard C-style escape
sequences (e.g.,
.Li \en
for newline,
.Li \er
for carriage return,
.Li \et
for tab).
.It
The backslash character
.Pq Li \e
is escaped as
.Li \e\e .
.It
All other non-printable characters are rendered as three-digit octal
sequences preceded by a backslash
.Pq e.g., Li \e001 .
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It 0
Success.
.It >0
An error occurred (e.g., a file could not be opened).
.El
.Sh EXAMPLES
To view hidden characters:
.Pp
.Dl $ vis file.bin
.Pp
To restore a file from its visible representation:
.Pp
.Dl $ unvis encoded.txt > original.bin
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr cat 1
